  "texts": [
    "Hence, the resulting soliton metric g on M 4 = B × ρ R 2 is locally isometric to the Riemannian product of (B 2, g B) with (R 2, h nil), where h nil is the Euclidean metric.",
    "Notice, however, that (M, g) cannot be globally isometric to a product, since the horizontal lift of a closed geodesic in (B 2, g B) representing a 1 is not closed.",
    "One dimensional base.Since harmonic maps from one-dimensional manifolds are geodesics, Proposition 3.8 implies that solutions of the harmonic-Einstein equations in this case give rise to locally homogeneous Ricci solitons.",
    "Homogeneous Ricci solitons are solvsolitons by [BL22,BL23a], so the solitons coming from solutions of the twisted harmonic-Einstein equations over a one-dimensional base must be quotients of solvsolitons [Lau11]; see also Example 4.27 in [Lot07].",
    "In this situation, we can describe the resulting homogeneous manifold in more familiar terms as follows.Let (M, g) be a Ricci soliton with a twisted N-action coming from a solution (g B, ρ, h) of the twisted harmonic-Einstein equations, and such that dim B = 1."
